# hostpanel-nginx — Test Scenarios

## Prerequisites
- Panel running on :2082, logged in as admin
- At least one hosting user exists (e.g. `testuser`)
- A DNS zone for `testdomain.com` exists in the DNS panel
- `SERVER_IP` set in `.env` so A records are auto-created

---

## SCENARIO 1: Provision a website
Steps:
1. Navigate to Websites → "Add Website"
2. Enter `testdomain.com` and select user `testuser`
Expected:
- Success; `testdomain.com` appears in list with status "active"
- `/home/testuser/public_html/testdomain.com/index.html` exists on server
- `/opt/hostpanel/nginx/vhosts/testdomain.com.conf` exists
- `curl http://testdomain.com` returns the default "You're live!" page
- DNS zone in DNS panel is NOT modified (nginx does not own DNS)

## SCENARIO 2: Add a subdomain
Steps:
1. Websites → click `testdomain.com` → "Add Subdomain"
2. Enter `blog`
Expected:
- `blog.testdomain.com` appears in subdomains list
- `/opt/hostpanel/nginx/vhosts/blog.testdomain.com.conf` exists
- DNS A record `blog.testdomain.com → SERVER_IP` created (nginx creates A records for subdomains only)

## SCENARIO 3: Issue SSL certificate
Steps:
1. Security → SSL → "Issue Certificate" → select `testdomain.com`
Expected:
- Status shows "pending" then polling resolves to "valid"
- `/etc/letsencrypt/live/testdomain.com/` exists on server

## SCENARIO 4: Enable Force HTTPS
Steps:
1. SSL page → toggle "Force HTTPS" for `testdomain.com`
Expected:
- `curl -I http://testdomain.com` returns 301 → `https://testdomain.com`
- Vhost file contains `return 301 https://`

## SCENARIO 5: Add a redirect
Steps:
1. Navigate to Websites → `testdomain.com` → Redirects → "Add Redirect"
2. Source path: `/old-page`, Destination: `https://testdomain.com/new-page`, Type: 301
Expected:
- `curl -I http://testdomain.com/old-page` returns 301 → destination URL
- Nginx vhost config contains the location block

## SCENARIO 6: Delete a subdomain
Steps:
1. Websites → `testdomain.com` → delete `blog.testdomain.com`
Expected:
- Vhost file removed; nginx reloaded
- DNS A record for `blog.testdomain.com` removed from DNS panel
- Files in `/home/testuser/public_html/blog.testdomain.com/` preserved

## SCENARIO 7: Delete a website — nginx-only cleanup
Steps:
1. Websites → `testdomain.com` → Delete
Expected:
- Nginx vhost removed and nginx reloaded
- SSL cert deleted (certbot delete)
- Subdomain vhosts cleaned up
- DNS zone `testdomain.com` is PRESERVED in DNS panel (nginx does not own DNS)
- FTP account, databases, and system user are PRESERVED (belong to other modules/core)
- Entry removed from `domains.json`

## SCENARIO 8: Delete DNS zone with associated website (cascade via hook)
Steps:
1. DNS panel → delete zone `testdomain.com` (domain must be provisioned in Websites)
Expected:
- Zone deleted from PowerDNS
- `hostpanel.hooks.domain_delete` hook fires → nginx plugin cleans up vhost and SSL
- Domain entry removed from `domains.json`
- FTP, databases, system user PRESERVED

## SCENARIO 9: Delete a hosting user (full cascade via core)
Steps:
1. Users → delete `testuser` (who has domains, SSL certs, subdomains)
Expected:
- Nginx vhosts for user's domains removed
- SSL certs deleted via certbot
- Subdomain vhosts removed
- DNS zones PRESERVED in DNS panel (DNS is core, user delete doesn't touch it)
- System user deleted by core (not nginx plugin)

---

## SCENARIO 10: Install nginx plugin when domains.json already has entries
Precondition: domains.json has existing records (e.g. from a previous install) but vhosts are missing
Steps:
1. Upload and install `hostpanel-nginx-1.0.0.zip`
2. Server restarts
3. Navigate to Websites
Expected:
- `on_startup` hook fires on restart
- Vhost files created for all domains in domains.json that were missing vhosts
- Existing vhost files are NOT overwritten (skip_if_exists=True)
- Confirmation: `ls /opt/hostpanel/nginx/vhosts/` shows vhosts for all registered domains

## SCENARIO 11: Install nginx plugin — does NOT overwrite existing nginx configs
Precondition: A vhost file already exists for `testdomain.com` with custom configuration
Steps:
1. Install/reinstall the nginx plugin
2. Server restarts
Expected:
- Existing vhost file for `testdomain.com` is unchanged (skip_if_exists=True in on_startup)
- `diff` between old and new vhost shows no changes

## SCENARIO 12: Uninstall nginx plugin (blocked without force)
Steps:
1. Packages → uninstall `hostpanel-nginx` (no force, domains exist)
Expected:
- 409 error: "Cannot uninstall: N domain(s) still provisioned. Use force=True to remove them."
- No vhosts deleted; server unchanged

## SCENARIO 13: Uninstall nginx plugin with force — DNS zones preserved
Steps:
1. Packages → uninstall `hostpanel-nginx` with force=true
Expected:
- All nginx vhost files deleted from `/opt/hostpanel/nginx/vhosts/`
- All SSL certs deleted via certbot
- Nginx reloaded (graceful)
- DNS zones in DNS panel PRESERVED — verify via DNS panel or `pdns_control list-zones`
- FTP accounts, databases, and system users PRESERVED
- domains.json and subdomains.json cleared
- Server restarts; "Websites" nav item disappears from sidebar
- SSL nav item remains (SSL is core)

---

## SCENARIO 14: Package compatibility check — compatible version
Steps:
1. Install a package with `"requires_core": [1, 0, 0]` against core 1.0.0
Expected:
- Package loads successfully
- `GET /cpanelapi/packages/installed` shows `"compatible": true`

## SCENARIO 15: Package compatibility check — incompatible version
Steps:
1. Build a test package with `"requires_core": [2, 0, 0]` in PLUGIN_MANIFEST
2. Install it against core 1.0.0
Expected:
- Package is installed by pip (pip doesn't know about hostpanel versions)
- On server restart, core logs: "Plugin requires core >= [2,0,0], but core is (1,0,0). Skipping."
- Plugin routers are NOT registered
- Nav item does NOT appear in sidebar
- `GET /cpanelapi/packages/installed` shows `"compatible": false`

## SCENARIO 16: DNS entries present — nginx provisions vhosts on startup
Steps:
1. Uninstall nginx plugin (force)
2. Using DNS panel, verify zones still exist for `testdomain.com`
3. Manually re-add domain registry entry (or reinstall nginx and re-add domain)
4. Reinstall nginx plugin
5. Restart server
Expected:
- on_startup runs and creates vhosts for all domains in domains.json
- Existing DNS zones are untouched
- `curl http://testdomain.com` resolves to the provisioned site
